Data Cleaning¶

  • Missing values: 'Churn Reason missed many values.
  • Further investigation: 'Churn Label', 'Churn Value' and 'Churn Score'
  • Check for duplicated rows
  • Correct data type: 'Total Charges'
  • Drop: 'CustomeID', 'Lat Long', 'Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Count', 'Country', 'State' and other potential columns from the above

In [9]:
# further investigate Churn Reason
raw_data['has_cr'] = raw_data['Churn Reason'].notnull().astype('int')
print(pd.crosstab(raw_data['has_cr'], raw_data['Churn Label'], margins=True))
raw_data.drop(['has_cr'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Churn Label    No   Yes   All
has_cr                       
0            5174     0  5174
1               0  1869  1869
All          5174  1869  7043

We confirmed that only rows recoreded as churned has the churn reason. This column cannot be included in modelling because it acts almost like a label itself. We can use it to derive why customer churn according which, the company can act proactively to keep the customers. This is can provide actionable insights after we identified churns using other columns. We will drop it after we have done the exploratory data analysis (EDA).

  • Churn Label and Churn Value are repliacted each other. We will use the Churn Label in EDA, and use Churn Value in modelling.
  • Churn Score is highly correlated with Churn Label, but it is not directly indicating Churn because records with the same Churn Value may or may not churn, ie Churn Value=80. From the documentation, we learn that 'Churn Score' is a feature produced by a trained IBM model that captured some critical factors about churn behaviour. Since it is already a product of another ML model, we will train and evaluate our own model with and without the 'Churn Score' and compare the difference.

As we see, there are only a few of them have high frequencies. Most of the cities have a counts that is lower than 100. We can group the city with counts < 100 as 'other'.

In [21]:
# group the city with counts < 100 as 'other'
other = counts.sort_values(by='City').index.tolist()[:-5]
EDA_data['City with other'] = EDA_data['City'].replace(other, 'other')
EDA_data.groupby('City with other').agg({'Churn Value':['sum', 'mean']})
Out[21]:
Churn Value
sum mean
City with other
Los Angeles 90 0.296053
Sacramento 26 0.240741
San Diego 50 0.333333
San Francisco 31 0.298077
San Jose 29 0.258929
other 1643 0.262712

If we group cities with frequencies < 100 as 'other', 'other' will have significantly high number of churns. This will create more noise for our model. The best decision so far is to drop 'City' because its caridinality is to high to be dealt with. If we keep it as it is, 'City' will cause more problems like the curse of high dimensionality.

Numerical Variables and Churn¶

In [24]:
# Numerical variables box plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(15, 10))
for var, subplot in zip(numerical, ax.flatten()):
    sns.boxplot(x='Churn Label', y=var, data=EDA_data, ax=subplot)

It is clear that 'Zip Code' has not impact on churn behaviour. On the other hand, 'Churn Score' is a key feature for indicating which customer will churn. What's more, customers having higher tenure months, lower monthly charges and higher total charges are less likely to churn. Lastly, it seems that the 'CLTV' does contribute much value in identifying customer who will or will not churn.

We can see that there are two pairs of features are higly correlated with each other:

  • 'Tenure Months' and 'Total Charges'
  • 'Monthly Charges' and 'Internet Service_Fiber optic'


This introduced the multi-colinearity problem. We will use PCA to solve this problem.

Apply PCA¶

In [66]:
# use standard scaler to scale data 
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, RobustScaler, MinMaxScaler

standard_scalar = StandardScaler()

model = PCA(n_components=1)
data_pca_1 = standard_scalar.fit_transform(data[['Tenure Months', 'Total Charges']])

Model Selection¶

In [75]:
# Aplly 10-Fold Cross-Validation
def cross_validation(model, X, y, cv=5):
    scoring = ['accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1']
    results = cross_validate(estimator=model,
                               X=X,
                               y=y,
                               cv=cv,
                               scoring=scoring,
                               return_train_score=True)

    return {
            "Mean Validation Accuracy": results['test_accuracy'].mean()*100,
            "Mean Validation Precision": results['test_precision'].mean(),
            "Mean Validation Recall": results['test_recall'].mean(),
            "Mean Validation F1 Score": results['test_f1'].mean(), 
            "Mean Training Accuracy": results['train_accuracy'].mean()*100,   
            "Mean Training Precision": results['train_precision'].mean(),
            "Mean Training Recall": results['train_recall'].mean(),
            "Mean Training F1 Score": results['train_f1'].mean(),
          }

Model Evaluation¶

In [87]:
from sklearn.metrics import plot_confusion_matrix, f1_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

for name, model in trained_models.items():
    # calculate accuracy
    acc = model.score(X_test, y_test)
    # make prediction
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    # calculate f1 score
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    # calculate auc roc
    y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    rocauc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
    # roc_curve
    fp_rate, tp_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
    
    # Plot fp_rate against tp_rate w/ a benchmark random classifier
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(18,6))
    ax1.plot(fp_rate, tp_rate)
    ax1.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r', linewidth=3)
    ax1.axis([0, 1, 0, 1])
    ax1.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    ax1.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    ax1.title.set_text('AUC Score = {}'.format(rocauc_score.round(4)))

    # plot confusion matrix
    labels=['No Churned','Churned']
    plot_confusion_matrix(logreg, X_test, y_test, 
                          display_labels=labels, 
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues, ax=ax2)
    ax2.title.set_text('F1 Score = {} | Accuracy = {}'.format(f1.round(4), acc.round(4)))
    plt.grid(b=None)
    fig.supylabel(name)
    plt.show()
